ðŸ”¹ ord() in Python:
The ord() function returns the ASCII (or Unicode) integer value of a given character.

| Function | Purpose                    | Example    | Output |
| -------- | -------------------------- | ---------- | ------ |
| `ord()`  | Char â†’ ASCII/Unicode value | `ord('a')` | 97     |
| `chr()`  | ASCII value â†’ Character    | `chr(97)`  | `'a'`  |
